description: Ultimately from Proto-Germanic *stam- (“to trip up; to stammer, stutter”), thereby related to German stumm (“mute”), Dutch stom (“dumb”). Doublet of stammer.

entries.meaning: A fall, trip or substantial misstep.

verbs.description: stumble (third-person singular simple present stumbles, present participle stumbling, simple past and past participle stumbled)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To trip or fall; to walk clumsily.
(intransitive) To make a mistake or have trouble.
examples: I always stumble over verbs in Spanish.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cause to stumble or trip.
(transitive, figurative) To mislead; to confound; to cause to err or to fall.
examples: One thing more stumbles me in the very foundation of this hypothesis.

entries.meaning: To strike or happen (upon a person or thing) without design; to fall or light by chance; with on, upon, or against.
examples: Forth as she waddled in the brake, / A grey goose stumbled on a snake.
